widgets_values:
• This is the "VAE Stack" group node, which allows loading separate VAE for SDXL and SD15 as well as piping through the VAE from the checkpoint, in case it has one baked in.

• Connect the "Checkpoint VAE" output directly to the "wifi SD_vae" node to use the checkpoint's VAE by default

nodes.title: Note — Accelerator LoRAs
widgets_values:
Personal recommendation PCM:

— https://github.com/G-U-N/Phased-Consistency-Model
— https://huggingface.co/wangfuyun/PCM_Weights/tree/main

The 4-step and 8-step versions with low- and normal-cfg I've tested and use regularly.

I used the 8-step normal-cfg version a lot with this workflow.
→ settings  :
   • sampler   : euler_ancestral_cfg_pp 
   • scheduler : normal 
   • steps     : 8
   • cfg       : ~2.0

nodes.title: Note ↑
widgets_values:
• The 'PixArt Resolution Select' node only has ratios to choose from, which might be confusing for some. The number is simply the ratio of the width to the height and is in the same ballpark as SDXL's resolutions.

   → ratio < 1 = portrait
   → ratio > 1 = landscape
   → ratio = 1 = square

nodes.title: Note ↓
widgets_values:
• There are not many PixArt finetunes out yet, but they seem to be easier to train than SDXL models, so hopefully we'll get to see more in time.

• The ones I've tried all produced great results, so I can only recommend them all and encourage you to test them yourself.

TwistedReality

extraMODE

PixelWaveSigma

nodes.title: Note ↓
widgets_values:
• This is the toggle to flick if you want to switch between SDXL and SD15 checkpoints. Simply select your checkpoint and set the toggle correspondingly.

• All 'xyz Input' nodes throughout the workflow serve the purpose of splitting the path for SDXL/SD15 and are controlled by this switch.

• Additionally there are two sets of accelerator and regular LoRA loaders prepared corresponding to SDXL and SD15 to keep them separate for convenience.

nodes.title: Hello Note
widgets_values:
—Hello and thanks for downloading this workflow!—

• Out of curiosity for the PixArt models I built a few workflows to try it out and found the prompt adherence as well as its style to be really noticeable and unique. Some prompts I've written months ago never really came out in SD generations, but now, for the first time, managed to.

• Unfortunately img2img and upscaling are not really great options at this point, not with PixArt only that is. While the UltimateSDUpscale node was quite capable of producing higher resolutions without the image falling apart, it still looked overly smooth and usually misproportioned.

• The simple solution to that is to only generate the 1st pass with PixArt and then use SD models further refine the image, similar to the refiner of SDXL in its early days.

• SDXL and SD15 both work great as refiners for PixArt and I definitely recommend trying out both.

• I've built the workflow with that in mind and facilitated the switch between SD15/SDXL models down to the literal virtual flick of a switch

nodes.title: Note ↓
widgets_values:
• Prompt adherence is PixArt's strong suit and works especially well with natural language prompts beyond the scope you typically dare use with SDXL or SD15 prompting, not to mention the tag-based Pony models.

• Feel free to test out some more verbose illustrations of the scene you imagine and you'll be surprised how much closer PixArt gets it compared to SD models

• The reason I've prepared two negative prompts is due to SD15's idiosyncracies in negatives, whereas SDXL usually doesn't need anywhere near as much. PixArt shares the same negative as SDXL in this case.

nodes.title: Note ↓
widgets_values:
• This is where the PixArt magic happens. 

• Set up like this with the AYS scheduler worked best for me, but might be different for you depending on the PixArt model you use.

nodes.title: Tutorial Note
widgets_values:
• To run PixArt models in ComfyUI you need the custom node pack "ComfyUI_ExtraModels", as well as the T5 text encoder, which is what allows PixArt to really shine with its prompt adherence.

The "ExtraModels" github :

— https://github.com/city96/ComfyUI_ExtraModels

• The T5 text encoder I would recommend is the FP16 version as it has "only" ~10GB total size compared to the FP32 with ~20GB and neglibly subtle differences.

Another option is to use the T5 encoder SD3 uses, in case you have that.
It is only ~5GB in size, but produces noticeably different results, so I don't use it. 

This link takes you to the passage with links to the files as well as instructions on where to put those :

— https://github.com/city96/ComfyUI_ExtraModels?tab=readme-ov-file#t5

nodes.title: Note →
widgets_values: • PixArt-Σ's latent encode/decode works uses the default SDXL VAE, in case you wonder.

nodes.title: Note ←
widgets_values:
• To keep the images intact in their upscaled state, I usually always plug in tile controlnets to avoid duplications and such that occur, when the pixel-area exceeds the model's scope of context.


SDXL tile controlnet :

— https://civitai.com/models/330313?modelVersionId=560349


SD15 tile controlnet :

— https://civitai.com/models/38784?modelVersionId=67566


• The models can be found through the ComfyUI Manager "Model Manager" search as well.

nodes.title: Note ←
widgets_values:
• The save node is preset to output .webp files at quality setting 97, which saves a lot of drive space and looks perfectly fine to me.

• So make sure to change its settings according to your preferences

nodes.title: Note ←
widgets_values: • Also note that there are 'Image Comparer' nodes set right above the 'Preview Image' nodes, so you can minimize/maximize the comparer as you see fit.
